[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \hypertarget{summary}{%
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \section{Summary}\label{summary}}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | This paper describes version 0.3.1 of spafe: a python package for audio
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | features extraction based on the Numpy
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (\protect\hyperlink{ref-numpy:2020}{Harris et al., 2020}) and Scipy
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (\protect\hyperlink{ref-scipy:2019}{Pauli Virtanen \& Vázquez‐Baeza,
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 2019}) libraries. Spafe implements various features extraction
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | techniques that can be used to solve a wide variety of recognition and
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | classification tasks (speaker verification, spoken emotion recognition,
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | spoken language identification etc.). The paper provides a brief
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | overview of the library’s structure, theory and functionalities.
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \hypertarget{statement-of-need}{%
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \section{Statement of need}\label{statement-of-need}}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | In speech processing, features extraction is essentially the estimation
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | of a parametric representation of an input signal. This is a key step in
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | any audio based modeling and recognition process (e.g.~speech
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | recognition, sound classification, speaker authentication etc.). There
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | are several speech features to extract, such as the Linear Frequency
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | Cepstral Coefficients (LFCC), Mel Frequency Cepstral Coefficients
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (MFCC), Linear Predictive Coding (LPC), and Constant-Q Cepstral
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | Coefficients (CQCC) etc. Each type of features has its own advantages
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | and drawbacks (e.g.~noise robustness, complexity, inter-components
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | correlation etc.) that can directly affect the researched topic.
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | Unfortunately, existing libraries for extracting these features
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (e.g.~librosa (\protect\hyperlink{ref-librosa:2015}{McFee et al.,
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 2015}), python\_speech\_features
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (\protect\hyperlink{ref-python_speech_features:2020}{Lyons et al.,
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 2020}), SpeechPy (\protect\hyperlink{ref-speechpy:2018}{Torfi, 2018})
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | and Bob (\protect\hyperlink{ref-bob:2017}{A. Anjos \& Marcel, 2017}))
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | are limited and mostly focus on one extraction technique (e.g.~MFCC),
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | thus it is hard to find reliable implementations of other features
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | extraction algorithms. Consequently, this slows down the research and
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | hinders the possibility of exploring and comparing these different
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | approaches. Hence, the need for \textbf{spafe}, a straightforward
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | solution that unites all these different techniques in one python
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | package.
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \hypertarget{introduction}{%
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \section{Introduction}\label{introduction}}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | The philosophy of spafe is keeping it simple, flexible and efficient in
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | order to reach a wide range of developers and researchers. Hence, spafe
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | is written in python 3 and only depends on Numpy
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (\protect\hyperlink{ref-numpy:2020}{Harris et al., 2020}) and Scipy
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | (\protect\hyperlink{ref-scipy:2019}{Pauli Virtanen \& Vázquez‐Baeza,
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 2019}). The library is heavily documented with the help of Sphinx and
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | tested using Pytest. Spafe supports \textbf{mono signals processing} and
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | has been tested with different sampling rates (e.g.~8kHz, 16Khz,
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 44.1kHz, 48kHz etc.).
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | Scripts in spafe are divided into four major groups (see Figure 1):
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | 
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \begin{table}[!h]
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \begin{center}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   |     \begin{tabular}{l*{4}{l}llllllllr}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   |       - \textbf{fbanks}       & filter banks implementations.\\
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   |       - \textbf{features}     & features extraction implementations.\\
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   |       - \textbf{frequencies}  & frequencies based features extraction implementations.\\
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   |       - \textbf{utils}        & helper functions for pre- \& post-processing and visualization etc. \\
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   |     \end{tabular}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \end{center}
[4e060040-933f-4471-9c12-1d55c97103b9/Paper Draft]   | \end{table}
